{"text": " Have you ever wondered what if you just kept going away from her? Imagine you fly off at the speed of light at 8.3 minutes you reach our sun. After four hours and six minutes you'd pass the farthest planet in our solar system and you'd have to get through this mess of comets and asteroids. How long do you think it takes you at the speed of light to get to the farthest object humans have ever set? It's 23 hours and 19 minutes. Now way beyond that at 29 days you'd hit this cloud of icy debris. Even traveling at the speed of light it takes a year and a half to go through it. But hold on, at four years in just as you're passing our nearest star. Something weird happens. You notice that you're in kind of a clearing. It turns out that our solar system is inside this local bubble. At about a hundred years you pass where the edge of our radio bubble is now. The distance our radio waves have traveled out into the universe. Compared to our whole galaxy, that distance is just that tiny blue spot. It would take you 27,000 years to reach the center and another 50,000 years to reach the other edge. And if you kept going and going and going for 46.5 billion years, you'd reach the edge of our observable universe. And beyond that, the light from whatever is out here still hasn't had time to reach Earth in the whole history of the universe. So maybe you'd find out if you like this video, subscribe.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.44, "text": " Have you ever wondered what if you just kept going away from her?", "tokens": [50364, 3560, 291, 1562, 17055, 437, 498, 291, 445, 4305, 516, 1314, 490, 720, 30, 50536], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14095030564528246, "compression_ratio": 1.7403508771929825, "no_speech_prob": 0.0294195469468832}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 3.44, "end": 7.44, "text": " Imagine you fly off at the speed of light at 8.3 minutes you reach our sun.", "tokens": [50536, 11739, 291, 3603, 766, 412, 264, 3073, 295, 1442, 4